speaking_head_in_silhouette: *PHILOSOPHICAL APPROACHES* :books:
———————————————————————————————————————————

• *Utilitarianism*: _The right action results in the greatest good for the greatest number of people._

`EXAMPLES`:
   > _The Trolley Problem_: Selecting to save five people over one.
   > _Nazi Data Usage_: Opting to use data to potentially help others.
   > _Vaccines_: Using vaccines to save more of the population even in the light of potential harm to a few.

• *Virtue Ethics*: _Right actions are based on virtues like prudence, strength, and courage. Doing what is right is doing what virtuous persons would do._

`EXAMPLES`:
>_WWJD_: People evaluating actions by asking “What Would Jesus Do?”
>_I Have A Dream_: Leaders looking up to embody MLK to set an example.

• *Social Contract Ethics*: _Society can define what is right and wrong through laws and social moores._

`EXAMPLES`:
>_No-Shoe Policy_: School social norm to introduce comfort to everyone.
>_Women Changing Surnames_: Social norm for wife to adopt husband’s surname.

• *Duty Based Ethics*: _Actions are right or wrong in themselves, regardless of the consequences based on ethical rules._

*SUBFIELDS*:
   • *Divine Command (Deontology)*: _Right actions are determined by supernatural powers and learned through revelation._
   • *Natural Law*: _The criteria for right actions can be derived from the workings of the natural world._
   • *Relationship Ethics*: _Right action derives from respecting vital relationships (child-parent, citizen-public servant, etc.)._
   • *Ethical Egoism*: _The right action is what best promotes my own interests directly or indirectly, now and in the future._
   • *Altruism*: _The right action comes from putting the interests of others above our own._
   • *Ethics of Care*: _Right actions are based in compassion, empathy, and care for ourselves, other people, and other forms of life._
   • *Aesthetic Ethic*: _Whatever is beautiful is good._

`EXAMPLES`:
>_Religious Crusades_: Should religious groups impose will on other groups by argument of divine right?
>_Social Empathy vs. Social Darwinism_: Should humans be bound to help each other? Nature vs. Nurture?
>_Extended Family Dynamics_: Should children be bound to serve their families no matter what? Individualism vs. Communalism?
>_Rise to Power_: Should one sacrifice others to promote their own interests and the interests of their constituents? House of Cards vs.
>_Social Martyrdom_: Should one sacrifice themselves and/or their constituents to promote others’ interests?
>_Parents Overly Caring for Kids_: Should one sacrifice more time to care for their kids because it’s compassionate?
>_Putting Down a Dog_: Should one punish a beautiful thing even if it’s responsible for ugly actions?

:scales: *JUSTICE APPROACHES* :books:
———————————————————————————————————————————

*What is Justice?*
> Distribution of wealth, a social order, punishing criminals, preventing crime, fairness, prejudice/racism, set of rules.

• *Comparative & Non-Comparative Justice*: _People deserve some things because they are unequal and others because they are equal._
• *Corrective, Retributive, & Distributive Justice*: _Upon breach of justice-based ethics, how is the breach treated? Correctivism (you broke my phone, you pay for it) vs. Retributivism (you broke my phone, I break your phone) vs. Distributivism (you broke my phone, but I have phone insurance)._
• *Conservative & Ideal Justice*: _It can be just to preserve an existing order, or to change to create a new, better order._
• *Procedural & Substantive Justice*: _Justice can be attained through just procedures or analysis of their outcomes._
• *Egalitarian Justice*: _Justice requires equality of advantages._
• *Rawl’s Theory of Justice*: _By deliberately ignoring our own identities, we can deduce what is just for all._

~ _Adam Braus_

<!channel>: Here’s some notes from Maribel’s Nutrition talk:
*NOTES* for Maribel’s Nutrition talk:

- Secrets to Healthy Eating:
      • Love good food
      • Trust yourself
      • Share the love/trust with yourself and those around you
      • RECOMMENDED READING: _Secrets of Feeding a Health Family_
      • CRITICAL QUESTION: _What affects the cultural aspect of food sharing?_
- Satter Eating Competence Model (ecSatter)
      • Competent Eating (permissiveness + discipline)
- Serving-Size Tricks
      • 1 cup ~ hand size
      • 3 oz ~ palm of your hand
      • 1 oz ~ length of your finger
      • CRITICAL QUESTION: _What does serving size really mean?_
          > Serving Size depends on each person’s individual biological traits (weight, height, sex, gender, age, physical activity)
- Vitamin A
      • Retinoids (pre-formed vitamin A)
- Vitamin E
      • Antioxidant
      •Anticoagulant
- Vitamin K
      • Blood clotting
      • Bone health (interdependent network)
- Vitamin D
      • “Sunshine” vitamin
      • Bone Health (calcium, phosphorus)
      • Cancer & Diabetes Prevention
      • Immune System/Blood Pressure
- Thiamin (B1)
- Riboflavin (B2)
- Niacin (B3)
      • LDL/HDL Regulation (supported by Omega-3s)
- Vitamin B6
- Vitamin B12
- Folate
- Vitamin C
      • Coenzyme
      • Antioxidant (iron absorption)
- Potassium
      • Fluid balance/blood filter
- Calcium
- Sulfur
- Vegan/Vegetarian Protein Sources
      • Seitan (similar to meat in texture)
      • Tofu/Tempeh (can form to food easily (good base))
      • Lentils/Beans
- Whole Grain vs. Refined vs. Enriched
      • Parts of whole grains are lost in refinement
      • Keep us full
      • Fiber and protien control glucose levels
- Resources
      • PickUpLimes
      • Yummly
      • Choose My Plate
      • Seasonal Food Guide
- Misconceptions
      • Frozen foods are not healthy (not really true)
- Plan Your First Meal (Tiny Habit)
      • Proportions for Fruits, Grains, Vegetables, Proteins, and Dairy
      • Fruits & Veggies -> 1/2 your plate
      • Calcium source
      • Protein
      • 1/2 of grains per day from whole grains
- Snacks:
      • Pair fruit/vegetable with protein (several hours of sustenance)
- CRITICAL QUESTION: _What alternatives are there for dairy?_
      • Kale (Calcium)
      • Bok Choy (Calcium)
- CRITICAL QUESTION: _Is butter bad?_
      • Saturated fats vs. Unsaturated fats
- CRITICAL QUESTION: _What’s the deal with proprietary blends in foods/supplements?_
      • USP Verification on Supplements
      • Foods/Drinks are Separately Verified and Tested than Supplements
      • Foods/Drinks are (for the most part) comprehensively studied and broken down
- CRITICAL QUESTION: _What’s the deal with probiotics?_
      • Depends on the probiotic!

<!channel> *Tip to drive the conversations forward with your industry partner:*
*1. - Schedule regular meetings ahead of time* to ensure you have for-certain touch points with your partner. With these, you can better plan your workflow, ensure you can clarify things with your partner, etc :calendar:
*2. - End all conversations with action items* - end meetings by sharing what you will do and make asks for what you’d like them to do. This requires some forethought of going into meetings/conversations knowing what you want and need from them. You can also close your meeting by scheduling a follow-up meetings to get the next action items rolling :baseball:.:memo:
*3. - Make and frame your own deadlines* - a message like one below will help you set expectations, frame deliverables, and ensure you get what you need, when you need it…  “We are hoping to have the idea finalized by DATE so that we have 9 weeks to build the product. We’ll need X and Y done before then, so, can we schedule a 30 min call the Friday and Tuesday before the date to ensure we have everything in place?” [send calendar invites]…  Own your efforts to drive the collaboration forward. :star-struck:
*4. Make asks specific* - Your partner will have a far easier time collaborating if you make your asks specific. For example, instead of saying “can you send us your data?” say “can you send us data on any of the following: Demographics, #years at company … or are there any fields you capture that you can send us.” The second example requires less thought and work on their end, making it easier for them to follow through.
…
I know that working with a partner can be frustrating, but know that these are the same dynamics you’ll face in the workplace, especially as you become senior engineers/PM and need to structure work for people on your team. We’re getting ample practice with this, so I hope you all use it as a way to strengthen your skills in collaboration and getting sh#t done!

attachments.title: Getting Started as a UX Researcher: Tips and Resources
attachments.text: More and more companies are beginning to recognize the importance of user-centered design. Understanding customers and designing solutions that serve their needs is quickly becoming a business priority. And because of that, the demand for UX researchers is growing. In some situations, people who don’t have any UX research experience are falling into this role at their company. And sometimes researchers from totally different sectors of the market are being hired to do user research. If you recently decided to make a career out of UX research, or if you transitioned into the role of UX researcher, this article is

attachments.title: Why You Only Need to Test with 5 Users
attachments.text: Elaborate usability tests are a waste of resources. The best results come from testing no more than 5 users and running as many small tests as you can afford.
